<sec id="sec-introduction">
  <title>1 Introduction</title>
  <p>In contemporary contexts, Comparative Judgment (CJ), as stated by
  Thurstone
  (<xref alt="1927" rid="ref-Thurstone_1927" ref-type="bibr">1927</xref>),
  is primarily associated with the method of
  <italic>Dichotomous</italic> Comparative Judgment (DCJ). Within this
  approach, a panel of judges evaluates the relative manifestation of a
  particular trait or quality within a pair of stimuli. The result of
  this evaluation produces a dichotomous value, indicating which
  stimulus in the pair has a higher degree of the trait or quality
  (<xref alt="Pollitt 2012a" rid="ref-Pollitt_2012a" ref-type="bibr">Pollitt
  2012a</xref>,
  <xref alt="2012b" rid="ref-Pollitt_2012b" ref-type="bibr">2012b</xref>).
  It has been shown that DCJ produces reliable and valid measures of the
  assessed traits and qualities
  (<xref alt="Lesterhuis 2018" rid="ref-Lesterhuis_2018" ref-type="bibr">Lesterhuis
  2018</xref>;
  <xref alt="van Daal 2020" rid="ref-vanDaal_2020" ref-type="bibr">van
  Daal 2020</xref>). Consequently, DCJ have been successfully employed
  to assess competences and traits in various domains, including
  education
  (<xref alt="Bartholomew et al. 2018" rid="ref-Bartholomew_et_al_2018" ref-type="bibr">Bartholomew
  et al. 2018</xref>;
  <xref alt="Lesterhuis 2018" rid="ref-Lesterhuis_2018" ref-type="bibr">Lesterhuis
  2018</xref>;
  <xref alt="Pollitt 2012b" rid="ref-Pollitt_2012b" ref-type="bibr">Pollitt
  2012b</xref>;
  <xref alt="van Daal 2020" rid="ref-vanDaal_2020" ref-type="bibr">van
  Daal 2020</xref>;
  <xref alt="Bartholomew and Williams 2020" rid="ref-Bartholomew_et_al_2020" ref-type="bibr">Bartholomew
  and Williams 2020</xref>), linguistics
  (<xref alt="Boonen, Kloots, and Gillis 2020" rid="ref-Boonen_et_al_2020" ref-type="bibr">Boonen,
  Kloots, and Gillis 2020</xref>), and psychology
  <styled-content style="color:red;">(citation needed)</styled-content>.
  In summary, DCJ presents itself as an alternative and efficient
  approach to measurement and evaluation that is reliable and valid
  across diverse domains.</p>
</sec>
